'''Novel ecosystems''' are human-built, modified, or engineered [[ecological niche|niches]] of the [[Anthropocene]]. They exist in places that have been altered in structure and function by human agency. Novel ecosystems are part of the [[human ecology|human]] [[Environment (biophysical)|environment]] and [[Ecological niche|niche]] (including [[urban area|urban]], [[suburban]], and [[rural]]), they lack natural analogs, and they have extended an influence that has converted more than three-quarters of wild Earth. These anthropogenic [[biome]]s include technoecosystems that are fuelled by powerful [[energy sources]] (fossil and nuclear) including ecosystems populated with technodiversity, such as roads and unique combinations of soils called [[technosols]]. [[Vegetation association]]s on old buildings or along field boundary stone walls in old agricultural [[landscape]]s are examples of sites where research into novel [[ecosystem ecology]] is developing.
==Overview==
[[Human society]] has transformed the planet to such an extent that we may have ushered in a new epoch known as the ''[[anthropocene]]''. The ecological niche of the anthropocene contains entirely novel ecosystems that include technosols, technodiversity, [[anthrome]]s, and the [[#Technosphere|technosphere]]. These terms describe the human ecological phenomena marking this unique turn in the evolution of Earth's history.<ref name="Odum05">{{cite book | last1=Odum | first1=E. P. | last2=Barrett | first2=G. W. | title=Fundamentals of ecology | publisher=Brooks Cole | isbn=978-0-534-42066-6 | year=2005 | pages=598 | url=http://www.cengage.com/search/totalsearchresults.do?N=16&image.x=0&image.y=0&keyword_all=fundamentals+of+ecology }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name="Stairs97">{{cite journal | last1=Stairs | first1=D. | title=Biophilia and technophilia: Examining the nature/culture split in design theory. | journal=Design Issues | volume=13 | issue=3 | pages=37–44 | jstor=1511939 | doi=10.2307/1511939}}</ref><ref name="Lugoa00">{{cite journal | last1=Lugoa | first1=A. E. | last2=Gucinski | first2=H. | title=Function, effects, and management of forest roads. | journal=Forest Ecology and Management | volume=133 | issue=3 | pages=249–262 | url=http://www.fsl.orst.edu/~waring/Umatilla%20Nat.%20Forest%20Wilcat%20Thinning%20and%20Fuel%20Mgmt%20Plan/Lugo%20and%20Gucinski%202000.pdf | doi=10.1016/s0378-1127(99)00237-6}}</ref><ref name="Barett00">{{cite journal | last1=Barrett | first1=G. W. | last2=Odum | first2=E. P. | title=The twenty-first century: The world at carrying capacity. | journal=BioScience | volume=50 | issue=4| pages=363–368 | url=http://www.hawaii.edu/publichealth/ecohealth/si/course-ecohealth/readings/Barrett_Odum-2000.pdf | doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2000)050[0363:TTFCTW]2.3.CO;2}}</ref><ref name="Naveh82">{{cite journal | last1=Naveh | first1=Z. | title=Landscape ecology as an emerging branch of human ecosystem science. | journal=Advances in Ecological Research | year=1982 | volume=12 | pages=189–237 | url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0065250408600793 | doi=10.1016/S0065-2504(08)60079-3}}</ref> The [[total human ecosystem]] (or anthrome) describes the relationship of the industrial technosphere to the [[Earth's spheres|ecosphere]].
Technoecosystems interface with natural life-supporting ecosystems in competitive and parasitic ways.<ref name="Odum05" /><ref name="Ellis11">{{cite journal | last1=Ellis | first1=E. C. | title=Anthropogenic transformation of the terrestrial biosphere. | journal=Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A | year=2011 | volume=369 | issue=1938 | pages=1010–1035 | doi=10.1098/rsta.2010.0331 | url=http://ecotope.org/people/ellis/papers/ellis_2011.pdf|bibcode = 2011RSPTA.369.1010E | pmid=21282158}}</ref> <ref name="Blersh05">{{cite journal | last1=Blersh | first1=D. M. | last2=Kangas | first2=P. C. | title=Autonomous behavior of a wetland soil technoecosystem. | journal=Environmental Engineering Science | volume=23 | issue=2 | pages=156–166 | url=http://www.nrmt.umd.edu/paperwetlandsoilmicrocosmpaper.pdf}}</ref> [[Eugene P. Odum|Odum]] (2001) <ref name="Odum01">{{cite journal | last1=Odum | first1=E. P. | title=The "Techno-Ecosystem". | journal=Bulletin of the Ecological Society of America | volume=82 | issue=2 | year=2001 | pages=137–138 | jstor=20168542}}</ref> attributes this term to a 1982 publication by Zev Naveh:<ref name="Naveh82"/> "Current urban-industrial society not only impacts natural life-support ecosystems, but also has created entirely new arrangements that we can call techno-ecosystems, a term believed to be first suggested by Zev Neveh (1982). These new systems involve new, powerful energy sources (fossil and atomic fuels), technology, money, and cities that have little or no parallels in nature."<ref name="Odum01" />{{rp|137}} The term technoecosystem, however, appears earliest in print in a 1976 technical report<ref name="Duffield76">{{citation | last1=Duffield | first1=C. | title=Geothermical technoecosystems and water cycles in arid lands. | publisher=University of Arizona, Office of Arid Lands Studies | year=1976 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=17kvAAAAYAAJ&q=%22technoecosystem%22&dq=%22technoecosystem%22&hl=en&ei=uyj6TYGlK_PZiAKzp7X2BA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA | pages=202}}</ref> and also appears in a book chapter (see <ref name="Wyatt84">{{cite journal | last1=Wyatt | first1=G. J. | title=Book Reviews | journal=The Economic Journal | volume=94 | issue=375 | year=1984 | pages=696–721 | jstor=2232737 | doi = 10.2307/2232737}}</ref> in Lamberton and Thomas (1982) written by [[Kenneth E. Boulding]]).<ref name="Lamberton83">{{cite book | editor1-last=Laberton | editor1-first=M. S. | editor2-last=Thomas | editor2-first=M. | chapter=Technology in the evolutionary process. | title=The trouble with technology. Explorations in the process of technological change. | place=London | publisher=Frances Pinter | year=1983 | pages=224 | isbn=0-312-81985-4}}</ref>
==Novel Ecosystems==
{{quote box | quote = A novel ecosystem is one that has been heavily influenced by humans but is not under human management. A working tree plantation doesn't qualify; one abandoned decades ago would. | source = Marris 2009<ref name="Ernest03">{{cite journal | last1=Marris | first1=E. | title=Ragamuffin Earth | journal=Nature | volume=460 | pages=450–453 | year=2009 | doi=10.1038/460450a | url=http://www.nature.com/news/2009/090722/pdf/460450a.pdf}}</ref>{{Rp|450}} | width=25% | align=left }}
Novel ecosystems "differ in composition and/or function from present and past systems".<ref name="Hobbs09">{{cite journal | last1=Hobbs | first1=R. J. | last2=Higgs | first2=E. | last3=Harris | first3=J. A. | title=Novel ecosystems: implications for conservation and restoration | journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution | volume=24 | issue=11 | pages=599–605 | year=2009 | doi=10.1016/j.tree.2009.05.012 | url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0169534709002018}}</ref> Novel ecosystems are the hallmark of the recently proposed anthropocene epoch. They have no natural analogs due to human alterations on global climate systems, invasive species, a global mass extinction, and disruption of the global [[nitrogen cycle]].<ref name="Hobbs09" /><ref name="Jackson09">{{cite journal | last1=Jackson | first1=S. T. | last2=Hobbs | first2=R. J. | title=Ecological restoration in the light of ecological history | journal=Science | volume=325 | issue=5940 | pages=567–569 | year=2009 | doi=10.1126/science.1172977 | url=http://environmentportal.in/files/Ecological%20restoration.pdf|bibcode = 2009Sci...325..567J }}</ref><ref name="Seastedt08">{{cite journal | last1=Seastedt | first1=T. R. | last2=Hobbs | first2=R. J. | last3=Suding | first3=K. N. | title=Management of novel ecosystems: Are novel approaches required? | journal=Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment | volume=6 | issue=10 | pages=547–553 | year=2008 | url=http://www.esajournals.org/doi/pdf/10.1890/070046 | doi=10.1890/070046}}</ref><ref name="Rockström09">{{cite journal | last1=Rockström | first1=J. | last2=Steffen | first2=W. | last3=Noone | first3=K. | last4=Persson | first4=Chapin | last5=Lambin | first5=E. F. | last6=Lenton | first6=T. M. | title=A safe operating space for humanity | journal=Nature | volume=461 | issue=7263 | pages=472–475 | doi=10.1038/461472a | url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v461/n7263/full/461472a.html | pmid=19779433|bibcode = 2009Natur.461..472R | date=September 2009|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Novel ecosystems are creating many different kinds of dilemmas for [[conservation biology|conservation biologists]].<ref name="Lindenmayer08">{{cite journal | last1=Lindenmayer | first1=D. B. | last2=Fischer | first2=J. | last3=Felton | first3=A. | last4=Crane | first4=M. | last5=Michael | first5=D. | last6=Macgregor | first6=C. | title=Novel ecosystems resulting from landscape transformation create dilemmas for modern conservation practice | journal=Conservation Letters | volume=1 | issue=3 | pages=129–135 | doi=10.1111/j.1755-263X.2008.00021.x | url=http://fog.ccsf.cc.ca.us/ldigirol/documents/novelecosystemscreatedilemmasformodernconservation.pdf|display-authors=etal}}</ref> On a more local scale, abandoned lots, agricultural land, old buildings, field boundary stone walls or residential gardens provide study sites on the history and dynamics of ecology in novel ecosystems.<ref name="Ernest03" /><ref name="Colliera12">{{cite journal | last1=Collier | first1=M. J. | title=Field boundary stone walls as exemplars of "novel" ecosystems | journal=Landscape Research | pages=1–10 | doi=10.1080/01426397.2012.682567 | year=2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Archibald|first=Carla L.|last2=McKinney|first2=Matthew|last3=Mustin|first3=Karen|last4=Shanahan|first4=Danielle F.|last5=Possingham|first5=Hugh P.|date=2017-06-01|title=Assessing the impact of revegetation and weed control on urban sensitive bird species|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/ece3.2960/abstract|journal=Ecology and Evolution|language=en|volume=7|issue=12|pages=4200–4208|doi=10.1002/ece3.2960|issn=2045-7758}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rogers|first=Andrew M.|last2=Chown|first2=Steven L.|date=2014-01-01|title=Novel ecosystems support substantial avian assemblages: the case of invasive alien Acacia thickets|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/ddi.12123/abstract|journal=Diversity and Distributions|language=en|volume=20|issue=1|pages=34–45|doi=10.1111/ddi.12123|issn=1472-4642}}</ref>
===Anthropogenic biomes=== {{see also|Total Human Ecosystem}} {{quote box | quote = Anthropogenic biomes tell a completely different story, one of “human systems, with natural ecosystems embedded within them”. This is no minor change in the story we tell our children and each other. Yet it is necessary for sustainable management of the biosphere in the 21st century.<ref name="Ellis08">{{cite journal | last1=Ellis | first1=E. C. | last2=Ramankutty | first2=N. | year=2008 | title=Putting people in the map: Anthropogenic biomes of the world | journal=Frontiers in Ecology and the Environment | volume=6 | pages=439–447 | url=http://ecotope.org/people/ellis/papers/ellis_2008.pdf | doi=10.1890/070062}}</ref>{{Rp|445}} | width = 25% | align = right}}
Ellis (2008)<ref name="Ellis08" /> identifies twenty-one different kinds of anthropogenic biomes that sort into the following groups: 1) dense settlements, 2) villages, 3) croplands, 4) rangeland, 5) forested, and 6) wildlands. These anthropogenic biomes (or anthromes for short) create the technosphere that surrounds us and are populated with diverse technologies (or technodiversity for short). Within these anthromes the human species (one species out of billions) appropriates 23.8% of the global net primary production. "This is a remarkable impact on the biosphere caused by just one species." <ref name="Haber07">{{cite journal | last1=Haber | first1=H. | last2=Erb | first2=H. | last3=Krausmann | first3=F. | last4=Gaube | first4=V. | last5=Bondeau | first5=A. | last6=Plutzar | first6=C. | title=Quantifying and mapping the human appropriation of net primary production in earth's terrestrial ecosystems | journal=PNAS | volume=104 | issue=31 | pages=12942–12947 | doi=10.1073/pnas.0704243104 | pmid=17616580 | bibcode=2007PNAS..10412942H | pmc=1911196|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
===Noosphere=== {{Main|Noosphere}} Noosphere (sometimes '''noösphere''') is the "[[theory of mind|sphere]] of human thought".<ref>Georgy S. Levit: The Biosphere and the Noosphere Theories of V. I. Vernadsky and P. Teilhard de Chardin: A Methodological Essay. International Archives on the History of Science/Archives Internationales D'Histoire des Sciences, 50 (144) - 2000: S. 160-176 {{cite web |url=http://www2.uni-jena.de/biologie/ehh/personal/glevit/Teilhard.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-05-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050517081543/http://www2.uni-jena.de/biologie/ehh/personal/glevit/Teilhard.pdf |archivedate=2005-05-17 |df= }}</ref> The word is derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''νοῦς'' ([[nous]] "[[mind]]") + ''σφαῖρα'' (sphaira "[[sphere]]"), in lexical analogy to "[[Earth's atmosphere|atmosphere]]" and "[[biosphere]]".<ref>"[...]he defined noosphere as the 'thinking envelope of the biosphere' and the 'conscious unity of souls'" David H. Lane, 1996, "The phenomenon of Teilhard: prophet for a new age" p.4 https://books.google.com/books?id=QrwityQkdxkC</ref> Introduced by [[Pierre Teilhard de Chardin]] 1922 <ref>In 1922, Teilhard wrote in an essay with the title 'Hominization': "And this amounts to imagining, in one way or another, above the animal biosphere a human sphere, a sphere of reflection, of conscious invention, of conscious souls (the noosphere, if you will)" (1966, p. 63) It was a neologism employing the Greek word noos for "mind." ( Teilhard de Chardin, "Hominization" (1923), "The Vision of the Past" pages 71,230,261 https://books.google.com/books?id=GnwPAQAAIAAJ )</ref> in his [[Cosmogenesis]]".<ref>Tambov State Technical University: [http://www.tstu.ru/win/kultur/nauka/vernad/uchver.htm Russian Scientist V.I.Vernadsky], in Russian</ref> Another possibility is the first use of the term by [[Édouard Le Roy]], who together with [[Pierre Teilhard de Chardin|Chardin]] was listening to lectures of [[Vladimir Vernadsky]] at [[Sorbonne]]. In 1936 [[Vladimir Vernadsky|Vernadsky]] presented on the idea of the Noosphere in a letter to [[Boris Leonidovich Lichkov]] (though, he states that the concept derives from Le Roy).
===Technosphere=== The technosphere is the part of the environment on Earth where technodiversity extends its influence into the biosphere.<ref name="Barett00"/><ref name="Naveh82"/><ref name="Palm96">{{cite journal | last1=Palm | first1=V. | last2=Östlund | first2=C. | title=Lead and zinc flows from technosphere to biosphere in a city region | journal=Science of the Total Environment | volume=192 | issue=1 | pages=95–109 | year=1996 | doi=10.1016/0048-9697(96)05301-6}}</ref> "For the development of suitable [[restoration (ecology)|restoration]] strategies, a clear distinction has to be made between different functional classes of natural and cultural solar-powered biosphere and fossil-powered technosphere landscapes, according to their inputs and throughputs of energy and materials, their organisms, their control by natural or human information, their internal [[self-organization]] and their regenerative capacities."<ref name="Naveh98">{{cite journal | last1=Naveh | first1=Z. | title=Ecological and cultural landscape restoration and the cultural evolution towards a post-industrial symbiosis between human society and nature | journal=Restoration Ecology | year=2004 | volume=6 | issue=2 | pages=135–143 | doi=10.1111/j.1526-100X.1998.00624.x}}</ref> The weight of Earth's technosphere has been calculated as 30 trillion tons, a mass greater than 50 kilos for every square metre of the planet's surface.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2016/11/161130085021.htm |title=Earth's 'technosphere' now weighs 30 trillion tons |publisher=Science Daily |date=30 November 2016|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref>
===Technoecosystems=== The concept of technoecosystems has been pioneered by ecologists [[Howard T. Odum]] and Zev Naveh. Technoecosystems interface with and are competitive toward natural systems. They have advanced technology (or technodiversity) money-based [[market economies]] and have a large [[ecological footprint]]s. Technoecosystems have far greater [[energy use|energy requirements]] than natural ecosystems, excessive [[water consumption]], and release [[toxic]] and [[eutrophication|eutrophicating]] chemicals.<ref name="Odum05" /><ref name="Naveh82" /><ref name="Odum01" /><ref name="Naveh98" /> Other ecologists have defined the extensive [[street network|global network of road system]]s as a type of technoecosystem.<ref name="Lugoa00" />
===Technoecotypes=== "Bio-agro- and techno-ecotopes are spatially integrated in larger, regional landscape units, but they are not structurally and functionally integrated in the ecosphere. Because of the adverse impacts of the latter and the great human pressures on bio-ecotopes, they are even antagonistically related and therefore cannot function together as a coherent, sustainable ecological system."<ref name="Naveh98" />{{rp|136}}
===Technosols=== {{main|Technosols}}
Technosols are a new form of ground group in the [[World Reference Base for Soil Resources]] (WRB).<ref name="FAO06">{{citation | last=FOA (Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations) | year=2006 | title=World reference base for soil resources 2006. A framework for international classification, correlation and communication | edition=2nd | journal=World Soil Resour Rep | volume=132 | pages=145}}</ref> Technosols are " mainly characterised by anthropogenic parent material of organic and mineral nature and which origin can be either natural or technogenic."<ref name="Monserie09">{{cite journal | last1=Monserie | first1=M. | last2=Watteau | first2=F. | last3=Villemin | first3=G. | last4=Ouvrard | first4=S. | last5=Morel | first5=J. | title=Technosol genesis: identification of organo-mineral associations in a young Technosol derived from coking plant waste materials | journal=J Soils Sediments | year=2009 | volume=9 | pages=537–546 |doi=10.1007/s11368-009-0084-y | url=http://www.springerlink.com/content/407m0t6841824365/}}</ref>{{rp|537}}
===Technodiversity=== Technodiversity refers to the varied diversity of technological artifacts that exist in technoecosystems.<ref name="Stairs97"/><ref name="Cooper00">{{cite journal | last1=Cooper | first1=B. | title=Modelling research and development: How do firms solve design problems? | journal=Journal of Evolutionary Economics | volume=10 | pages=395–413 | url=http://www.springerlink.com/content/m2bd9yrn8cq7g9b2/ | doi=10.1007/s001910000040 | year=2000 | issue=4}}</ref><ref name="Sorensen02">{{cite book | editor-last=Sorensen | editor-first=K. H. | editor2-last=Williams | editor2-first=R. | title=Shaping technology, guiding policy: Concepts, spaces and tools. | place=Cheltenham, UK & Northampton | year=2002 | pages=404 | isbn=1-84064-649-7 | publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing Ltd}}</ref><ref name="Adams09">{{cite journal | last1=Adams | first1=C. | title=Applied catalysis: A predictive socioeconomic history | journal=Topics in Catalysis | volume=52 | issue=8 | pages=924–934 | doi=10.1007/s11244-009-9251-z | year=2009}}</ref><ref name="Sandén05">{{cite journal | last1=Sandén | first1=B. A. | title= Near-term technology policies for long-term climate targets—economy wide versus technology specific approaches | journal=Energy Policy | volume=33 | issue=12 | pages=1557–1576 | doi=10.1016/j.enpol.2004.01.012 | year=2005 | last2=Azar | first2=C}}</ref><ref name="Rammert02">{{cite book | editor1-last=Williams | editor1-first=R. | editor2-last=Sörensen | editor2-first=K. H. | chapter=The cultural shaping of technologies and the politics of technodiversity. | title=Shaping Technology, Guiding Policy: Concepts, Spaces & Tools | place=Cheltenham | publisher=Edward Elgar | year=2002 | pages=173–194 | isbn=1-84064-649-7}}</ref>
